ce:section.ce:para:
QDs, as another member of carbon-based nanomaterials, enjoy unique size dependence and luminescence properties. Interestingly, the integration of QDs with MIPs can address of the huge challenges of QDs which is selectivity. In 2019, Liu and co-workers [74], developed a new probe (MIP@SiO2@QDs) with high FL properties for the sensitive detection of 2,4,6‐trichlorophenol (2,4,6‐TCP). In this study, authors employed APTS as the functional monomer, TEOS as the cross-linker, and QDs as the signal sources. The FL quenching introduced a LOD of 0.9 μM and also recorded a recovery rate of 98–105.8 % for analyzing real samples. Due to several advantages of combining silica materials with QDs including accessibility silicon sources and biocompatibility, in another study conducted by Xu et al. [75], a novel approach was employed to fabricate sensing platform based on Si QDs@SiO2@MIPs for catechol (CT) detection (Fig. 3
                        ). Following the initial step involved the modification of Si QDs with APTS, the CT was successfully contacted with the modified Si QDs. In this protocol, Si QDs@SiO2@MIPs was synthesized by sol-gel method and using TEOS. The FL intensity of Si QDs@SiO2@MIPs was significantly decreased upon interaction with CT which indicated a dynamic quenching effect. The performance of the devised strategy was assessed through the detection of the target analyte in actual water samples which revealed satisfactory recoveries rate within the range of 97.77–101.70 %. In another similar application of carbon-based nanomaterials in the structure of MIPs-based silica, a mesoporous structured molecularly imprinted assay with dual-emission capability was developed to sensitive ratiometric identification of diniconazole (DNZ) [76]. Similarly, Liu and colleagues [77], reported a highly sensitive and selective ratiometric fluorescent sensor based on a core-shell nanohybrid with MIPs for detection of 4-NP. The principle of this study was achieved through the process of FL resonance energy transfer between photoluminescent CDs and 4-NP. The synthesis of the probe was conducted by conjugation of organosilane-functionalized CDs with silica-coated cadmium selenide (CdSe) QDs through the formation of silicon (Si)-oxygen (O) bonds. Furthermore, the nanohybrids were decorated by attaching a MIP layer on the ratiometric fluorescent sensor through sol-gel polymerization technique. Under optimal conditions, the FL intensity has in direct relationship with 4-NP concentration. This platform was able to detect the target with a LOD and linear range of 0.026 μg mL−1 and 0.051–13.7 μg mL−1, respectively. As shown in Fig. 4
                        , similarly, the concept of exploiting CDs in the ratiometric FL probe based on MIPs-silica materials developed for chloramphenicol detection in milk [78].The comparison of ratiometric sensors with single signal sensors reveals that the superiority of ratiometric sensors lie on several benefits such as their capacity to self-calibrate, lower interference, high accuracy. In another example of using carbon-based nanomaterials in the structure of MIPs-based silica probes, Zhou and co-workers [79], presented a novel probe (SiO2@QDs@MIPs) for the development of a FL -based MIP in terms of dibutyl phthalate (DBP) detection. For this purpose, the probe was successfully synthesized by using manganese-doped zinc sulfide QDs (Mn-doped ZnS QDs) and anchoring a MIPs layer on the surface of SiO2 nanoparticles (Fig. 5
                        ). The performance of developed probe towards DBP was evaluated by decrease of FL intensity which related to the extent of DBP binding. The developed approach offered efficient, and reliable analytical instrument for the on-site identification of DBP in linear range of 5–50 μM.

Generally, the principle of optical probes is converting light into an electrical signal. Elaborately, fluorescent molecules emit light when excited by a specific wavelength [99]. In the realm of polymers, functional monomers possess a reactive or functional group, enabling them to engage in interactions with the template molecule during the process of polymerization [100]. Thereby, the careful selection of a functional monomer plays a pivotal role in determining the selectivity and sensitivity of MIP-based sensors, as it directly influences the binding affinity and specificity of the resulting MIP [101]. In addition, functional monomers have a crucial role in enhancing the stability and mechanical strength of MIP-silica composites [102]. Several functional monomers have been utilized in the synthesis of polymers for biomedical analytes. Among various types of them, APTS, (3-isocyanatopropyl)triethoxysilane, and methacrylic acid were used frequently. In 2021, Yang et al. [103], designed a new ratiometric FL probe to detect ascorbic acid. For this purpose, the reference signal was introduced by embedding CdTe sulfide (CdTeS) QDs in silica shell (Fig. 8
                        ). Furthermore, zinc cadmium sulfide QDs (ZCS QDs) were incorporated within a three-dimensional network of molecularly imprinted polymer to presented response signal. The functional monomer and cross-linker used in this system were APTS and TEOS, respectively. In detail, the binding of ascorbic acid and APTS was conducted based on interaction of amino groups on the surface of APTS and hydroxyl groups of ascorbic acid. In the presence of ascorbic acid, the emission of FL from ZnCdS QDs@MIP exhibited specific quenching. A linear model was developed by correlating the FL intensity ratios (F530/F705) of ZnCdS QDs@MIP and CdTeS QDs@SiO2 with a wide linear range of ascorbic acid (1–500 μM). The reliability of the proposed probe for real sample analysis was evaluated by detecting ascorbic acid in vitamin C tablets, yielding satisfactory outcomes. Although semiconductor nanocrystal conjugated MIPs can introduce high-performance probes, their environmental issue is undeniable. Indeed, semiconductor nanocrystals, which are also known as QDs, may contain heavy metals like cadmium, lead, or arsenic. If these metals are not disposed of or handled properly, they can pose serious risks to both the environment and human health. These materials have the potential to release toxic components into the environment, which can cause a lot of harm [104]. In another example, Samarin and colleagues [105], constructed a novel and sensitive optical probe exploiting GQDs embedded with silica MIP for the quantitative analysis of metronidazole in plasma samples (Fig. 9
                        ). In this study, the copolymerization of APTS on the surface of silica-embedded GQDs and TEOS presented high affinity and selectivity MIPs. The developed probe exhibited a robust and pronounced FL response at 450 nm upon excitation at 365 nm. When the target added to system, the FL signal significantly reduced. In detail, the extent of quenching observed showed a direct correlation with the concentration of metronidazole in a linear range from 0.2 to 15 μM. Furthermore, the reported FL nanosensor was able to detect metronidazole with a LOD of 0.15 μM. Similarly, Shariati and co-workers [106], used APTS as functional monomer in the structure of FL probe (silica-green source carbon dots, GSCDs) for the precise detection of phenobarbital, a commonly prescribed drug for epilepsy treatment. For this purpose, the synthesis of GSCDs was accomplished via a hydrothermal method employing Cedrus as the carbon source. Furthermore, the surface of GSCDs were decorated with silica materials layer for providing an appropriate formation substrate of MIPs, which conducted by copolymerization of TEOS and APTS through van der Waals forces and the hydrogen bond interactions. In the presence of the target, the FL signal of the probe was decreased due to rebinding of phenobarbital molecules with the cavities of the MIPs. Under optimal conditions, the developed sensor could able to quantify phenobarbital with a linear range from 0.4 to 34.5 nM and a LOD of 0.1 nM. In addition, the developed sensor was able to detect phenobarbital in blood plasma samples. Most recently, Zhang and Chen [107], prepared a novel FL probe composing QD/mesoporous silica materials/MIP (QD/MS/MIP) for tetracycline quantification. In this study, according to the using (3-isocyanatopropyl)triethoxysilane (ICPTES) as the functional monomer and TEOS as cross-linker, the sol-gel approach was employed to synthesize mesoporous silica materials/MIPs. After removal of the template, the formation of a binding site facilitated the establishment of a hydrogen bonding interaction between the resultant cavity and the target molecule. Under normal circumstances, the FL quenching phenomenon was conducted by transferring energy from QDs to the complex.
